# mockspace-template

Reusable template engine and agent-file generator extracted from mockspace's `src/render_*.rs` modules. Provides Jinja2-syntax template rendering (via `minijinja`) over `serde::Serialize` contexts, plus a `Platform` trait that abstracts the differences between agent surfaces (Claude Code, GitHub Copilot, future tools) so the same template tree renders to multiple platform-specific output destinations.

Consumed by the mockspace binary, by homma, and by any tool that needs to render templates against typed contexts or emit agent integration files.

## What this crate provides

The public surface lives in three layers:

| Layer | Item | Role |
|---|---|---|
| Template | `Template` | A single compiled template; rendered against a `serde::Serialize` context. Wraps `minijinja::Template<'_, '_>`. |
| Template | `TemplateEnv` | Registry of named templates with shared filters and globals. Wraps `minijinja::Environment<'_>`. |
| Template | `RenderError` | Error type for template parse / render / IO failures. |
| Platform | `Platform` (trait) | Abstracts agent platform specifics: output path mapping, frontmatter format, hook-helper injection, settings-file emission. |
| Platform | `ClaudePlatform` | Built-in impl for the Anthropic Claude Code surface (`.claude/rules/`, `paths:` frontmatter, `hookSpecificOutput` JSON). |
| Platform | `CopilotPlatform` | Built-in impl for the GitHub Copilot CLI surface (`.github/instructions/`, `applyTo:` frontmatter, flat JSON decisions). |
| Platform | `HookDecl` | Declarative hook description passed to `Platform::settings_file()` so the platform can emit its own settings file shape. |
| Renderer | `AgentRenderer<'env, P: Platform>` | Walks a source template directory, renders each `.md.tmpl` against a context, emits per-platform output trees. |
| Renderer | `walk_template_tree(env, src, dst, ctx)` | Generic recursive renderer for non-agent template trees (workspace docs etc.). Preserves source structure with `.tmpl` stripped. |
| Renderer | `RenderReport` | Per-call summary listing every file written, with sizes and timing for diagnostic output. |

## Template engine — minijinja wrapper

The template engine wraps `minijinja` so consumers get full Jinja2 syntax: `{{ var }}` substitutions, `{% for %}` loops, `{% if %}` conditionals, `{% include %}` partials, and filters (`{{ name | upper }}`).

### Why minijinja over alternatives

- Lighter compiled footprint than `tera` (~100KB vs ~300KB), faster build times.
- Jinja2-syntax clone by Armin Ronacher (Jinja's original author); battle-tested semantics consumers know from Python.
- Cleaner internals; `no_std`-friendlier than tera for future substrate adoption.
- Uses `serde::Serialize` for template context, which decouples the engine from any specific config type.

### Building a Template

A consumer assembles a `TemplateEnv`, registers templates by name, then renders each by name against a context:

```rust
use mockspace_template::{TemplateEnv, RenderError};
use serde::Serialize;

#[derive(Serialize)]
struct Ctx { project_name: String, version: String }

let mut env = TemplateEnv::new();
env.add_template("readme", "# {{ project_name }} v{{ version }}\n")?;

let ctx = Ctx { project_name: "homma".into(), version: "0.1.0".into() };
let rendered = env.get_template("readme")?.render(&ctx)?;
```

### Context model

Any `T: serde::Serialize`. The crate does NOT define a typed context schema; consumers serialize whatever shape they want, and templates reference field paths.

Mockspace passes its `Config` value (typed). Homma passes a value constructed via `IntoMockspaceConfig` from its own typed config. Both produce the same template-visible vocabulary; templates work uniformly across consumer schemas.

### Autoescape policy

**Off by default.** The templates emit Markdown, Rust source, shell scripts, and other plain-text formats. HTML escaping would corrupt these outputs.

Consumers that render HTML templates may enable autoescape per-template via `TemplateEnv::set_auto_escape(...)`; the default keeps text passthrough clean.

### Strict-mode setting

**On.** Undefined variables in templates produce render-time errors, not silent empty strings. Catches typos and missing context fields immediately rather than hiding bugs in rendered output.

### Custom filter / function registrations

Empty in v1. Future additions tracked in `BACKLOG.md.tmpl`.

## Platform trait

The `Platform` trait abstracts agent-platform specifics so the same template tree renders to multiple targets without changing the source `.md.tmpl` files.

```rust
use std::path::{Path, PathBuf};

pub trait Platform {
    /// Identifier used in templates and CLI output ("claude", "copilot").
    fn name(&self) -> &'static str;

    /// Translate a logical name from the source template tree to the
    /// platform's destination path under repo_root.
    ///
    /// Logical names are derived from source paths by stripping `.md.tmpl`.
    /// Examples:
    ///   ClaudePlatform: "rules/foo" -> "<repo>/.claude/rules/foo.md"
    ///   CopilotPlatform: "rules/foo" -> "<repo>/.github/instructions/foo.instructions.md"
    fn output_path(&self, repo_root: &Path, logical_name: &str) -> PathBuf;

    /// Generate the platform-specific frontmatter for a rule's
    /// applicability globs. Claude uses `paths:`, Copilot uses `applyTo:`.
    fn frontmatter(&self, applies_to: &[&str]) -> String;

    /// Generate the platform-specific hook helper snippet to inject at
    /// `{{ hook_helpers }}` template variable. Different shells per platform
    /// (Claude: hookSpecificOutput JSON; Copilot: flat JSON / plain text).
    fn hook_helpers(&self, repo_root: &Path) -> String;

    /// Platform-specific settings file (e.g. settings.json) emission.
    /// Returns Some((path, contents)) if the platform writes one; None otherwise.
    fn settings_file(&self, repo_root: &Path, hooks: &[HookDecl]) -> Option<(PathBuf, String)>;
}
```

### Why std `Option` / `Result` / `PathBuf` / `String` here

mockspace-template is the meta-tool layer; it does not consume the substrate stack (notko/arvo/hilavitkutin). The workspace's substrate-discipline rules (no bare `Option`/`Result`, no raw numerics, etc.) apply to consumers of the substrate, not to design tools that bootstrap the substrate.

When mockspace-template eventually lands in mockspace's live root (after homma validates the shape), substrate adoption is revisited (see `BACKLOG.md.tmpl`). v1 stays on std types to minimize cross-dependency surface and keep the crate small.

### Adding a new platform

External consumers can implement `Platform` on their own type to add support for Cursor, Codeium, or any future agent tool. Built-in impls (`ClaudePlatform`, `CopilotPlatform`) live in this crate; third-party impls live in the consumer.

## Built-in Platform impls

### ClaudePlatform

Output paths under `<repo_root>/`:

| Logical name | Output path |
|---|---|
| `rules/<name>` | `.claude/rules/<name>.md` |
| `skills/<name>` | `.claude/skills/<name>/SKILL.md` |
| `hooks/<name>` | `.claude/hooks/<name>.sh` |
| `agents/<name>` | `.claude/agents/<name>.md` |
| `instructions` (root) | `.claude/CLAUDE.md` |
| `settings` | `.claude/settings.json` |

Frontmatter shape:

```yaml
---
paths:
  - "**/*.rs"
  - "**/*.md"
---
```

Hook helpers body: ports the `CLAUDE_HOOK_HELPERS` const from mockspace's `src/render_agent.rs`. Wraps `hookSpecificOutput` JSON with `permissionDecision` / `additionalContext` keys; provides `_extract`, `allow`, `deny`, `context`, `_scope_or_allow` shell helpers.

### CopilotPlatform

Output paths under `<repo_root>/`:

| Logical name | Output path |
|---|---|
| `rules/<name>` | `.github/instructions/<name>.instructions.md` |
| `skills/<name>` | `.github/skills/<name>/SKILL.md` |
| `hooks/<name>` | `.github/hooks/<name>.sh` |
| `instructions` (root) | `.github/copilot-instructions.md` |
| `settings` | `.github/copilot/hooks.json` |

Frontmatter shape:

```yaml
---
applyTo: "**/*.rs,**/*.md"
---
```

Hook helpers body: ports the `COPILOT_HOOK_HELPERS` const from `src/render_agent.rs`. Flat JSON decisions (`{"permissionDecision":"deny","permissionDecisionReason":"..."}`); plain-text context output; different `_extract` shape for Copilot's stringified `toolArgs` field.

## AgentRenderer — orchestration

The `AgentRenderer` walks a source directory of `.md.tmpl` files and emits the rendered output per the platform's path conventions.

```rust
use mockspace_template::{TemplateEnv, AgentRenderer, ClaudePlatform, RenderReport};

pub struct AgentRenderer<'env, P: Platform> {
    env: &'env TemplateEnv,
    platform: P,
    src_root: PathBuf,
    dst_root: PathBuf,
}

impl<'env, P: Platform> AgentRenderer<'env, P> {
    pub fn new(
        env: &'env TemplateEnv,
        platform: P,
        src_root: PathBuf,
        dst_root: PathBuf,
    ) -> Self;

    /// Walk src_root, render each .md.tmpl, write to platform-derived
    /// output paths under dst_root. Returns a report of every file written.
    pub fn render_all<C: serde::Serialize>(
        &self,
        ctx: &C,
    ) -> Result<RenderReport, RenderError>;
}
```

The render loop:

1. Walk `src_root` recursively for `*.md.tmpl` files.
2. For each, derive the logical name: path relative to `src_root`, with `.md.tmpl` stripped, separator normalized to forward-slash.
3. Look up output path via `self.platform.output_path(&self.dst_root, &logical_name)`.
4. Compile the template (if not already in `env`) and render against `ctx`.
5. Ensure destination directory exists; write rendered contents.
6. Append entry to the `RenderReport`.

The renderer makes no assumption about how many platform passes a consumer wants. To render both Claude and Copilot outputs from one source tree, a consumer constructs two `AgentRenderer` instances with different platforms and runs both.

## Non-agent template rendering — walk_template_tree

For template trees that are not agent-specific (workspace-level docs, project README templates, etc.):

```rust
use mockspace_template::{TemplateEnv, RenderReport, RenderError, walk_template_tree};

pub fn walk_template_tree<C: serde::Serialize>(
    env: &TemplateEnv,
    src_root: &Path,
    dst_root: &Path,
    ctx: &C,
) -> Result<RenderReport, RenderError>;
```

Same shape as `AgentRenderer::render_all`, but the output path mapping preserves source structure verbatim with `.tmpl` stripped from filenames. No platform-specific path rewriting.

## RenderReport

Returned by both `AgentRenderer::render_all` and `walk_template_tree`. Lists every file written with its source template path, output path, byte count, and render duration. Consumers use it for progress reporting or post-render validation.

```rust
pub struct RenderReport {
    pub entries: Vec<RenderedFile>,
    pub total_bytes: u64,
    pub total_duration: std::time::Duration,
}

pub struct RenderedFile {
    pub source: PathBuf,
    pub destination: PathBuf,
    pub bytes_written: u64,
    pub duration: std::time::Duration,
}
```

## What this crate does NOT do

| Concern | Where it lives |
|---|---|
| Template authoring tools (interactive scaffolds, etc.) | mockspace binary CLI |
| TOML config parsing | `mockspace-config` |
| Git operations | homma (gix-based) |
| Lint runner | mockspace internals (viola will replace) |
| Design-round state machine | mockspace internals |
| Bench harness | `mockspace-bench-core` / `mockspace-bench-harness` / `mockspace-bench-macro` |

## Crate dependencies

- `minijinja` — full Jinja2 template language
- `serde` + `serde_derive` — context model
- `std` — `PathBuf`, `fs`, `io::Result`, `time::Duration`

No `notko`, `arvo`, `hilavitkutin`, or other substrate-stack deps. mockspace-template is meta-tool code; substrate adoption is deferred to the live-port round (see BACKLOG).

## Audit trail

Source modules in mockspace's live root that informed this design:

- `src/render_md.rs` — top-level Mustache-like substitution; this crate generalises to full Jinja2 via minijinja.
- `src/render_agent.rs` — agent-file rendering for Claude+Copilot; this crate extracts the platform-specific bits behind the `Platform` trait.
- `src/render.rs` — DOT/graph generation; NOT extracted (mockspace-specific).
- `src/render_design.rs` — DESIGN.md generation; NOT extracted (mockspace-specific).

